  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe deadargelim pass crashes on a module
containing musttail calls. The verifier reports two musttail violations after running
-passes=deadargelim:\n- cannot guarantee tail call due to mismatched return types (for a
musttail call to @B)\n- musttail call must precede a ret with an optional bitcast (for a
musttail call to @F38)\nThis indicates that the pass changed function signatures
(particularly return types) in the presence of musttail, breaking musttail's strict
requirements.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows the verifier errors immediately,
meaning the final IR after deadargelim is invalid. No other debug-only logs are available,
but based on the pass code, deadargelim can change function return types (remove dead
return components) and updates all direct call sites. It also reconstructs aggregate
returns at call sites by inserting extractvalue/insertvalue around call results when
return types change.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- In surveyFunction(), the pass carefully
avoids removing arguments if the function has musttail callers (HasMustTailCallers) or
contains musttail calls itself (HasMustTailCalls). However, it does not similarly protect
return values. As a result, it may decide to eliminate/alter return values of a function
that has musttail callers or musttail calls.\n- In removeDeadStuffFromFunction(), when a
callee's return type changes, the pass rewrites all callers. For non-void changes, it
synthesizes IR (insertvalue/extractvalue) to rebuild the old aggregate type at the call
site. If a call site is a musttail call, inserting any instruction between the musttail
call and the ret breaks musttail's rule that the musttail call must be immediately
followed by a ret returning (optionally via a bitcast) the call value. This explains the
second verifier error on the F36\u2192F38 musttail path.\n- Additionally, changing a
function's own return type in the presence of a musttail call result being returned
directly (e.g., C returning result of musttail to B) creates a mismatch between the
musttail call's return type and the function's return type, producing the first
\u201ccannot guarantee tail call due to mismatched return types\u201d error.\n- The
comment in surveyFunction() says: \"If we have any returns of musttail results - the
signature can't change\". The code sets HasMustTailCalls for terminating musttail calls,
but only uses that flag to force arguments live, not return values. That is the gap.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s)\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/DeadArgumentElimination.cpp\nInsertion after line 616 (right after
logging HasMustTailCallers):\n\nAdd the following block to force all return values live
when either the function has musttail callers or contains musttail calls:\n\n{\n  // If
this function has musttail callers or contains a terminating musttail\n  // call, we
cannot change its return type without violating musttail rules.\n  // Mark all return
values live to prevent signature changes.\n  if (HasMustTailCallers || HasMustTailCalls)
{\n    for (unsigned Ri = 0; Ri != RetCount; ++Ri) {\n      RetValLiveness[Ri] = Live;\n
MaybeLiveRetUses[Ri].clear();\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nThis is placed just before the code that
records return-value liveness into LiveValues:\n  // Now we've inspected all callers,
record the liveness of our return values.\n  for (unsigned Ri = 0; Ri != RetCount; ++Ri)\n
markValue(createRet(&F, Ri), RetValLiveness[Ri], MaybeLiveRetUses[Ri]);\n\nRationale:\n-
Ensures functions with musttail callers or musttail returns won't have their return type
changed, avoiding both kinds of musttail verifier failures:\n  - Mismatched caller/callee
return types for musttail sites.\n  - Extra instructions between musttail call and ret
introduced by aggregate reconstruction.\n- Matches the intent of the comment \"the
signature can't change\" and mirrors the existing protection that prevents argument
removal under these conditions.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by deadargelim
changing return types in the presence of musttail, which requires exact signature and
immediate ret constraints. By marking all return values live for functions that either
have musttail callers or contain (terminating) musttail calls, we prevent signature
changes that would violate musttail requirements. This preserves correctness without
broadening the pass's impact beyond necessary constraints and aligns with existing
handling for arguments under musttail conditions.",
